    "topic": "trigonometric-series",
    "difficulty": "hard",
    "solution": "<p>$\\begin{aligned} & \\text { Consider } \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{\\sin \\theta}{\\cos 3 \\theta} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{2 \\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta}{2 \\cos 3 \\theta \\cos \\theta} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{\\sin 2 \\theta}{2 \\cos 3 \\theta \\cos \\theta} \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{\\sin (30-\\theta)}{2 \\cos 3 \\theta \\cos \\theta} \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{E}=\\frac{1}{2}[\\tan 3 \\theta-\\tan \\theta] \\\\ & \\mathrm{A}=\\frac{1}{2}\\left[\\tan 9^{\\circ}-\\tan 3^{\\circ}+\\tan 27^{\\circ}-\\tan 9^{\\circ}+\\tan 81^{\\circ}-\\tan 27^{\\circ}\\right] \\\\ & \\therefore \\mathrm{A}=\\frac{1}{2}\\left[\\tan 81^{\\circ}-\\tan 3^{\\circ}\\right] \\\\ & \\therefore \\frac{\\mathrm{B}}{\\mathrm{A}}=2\\end{aligned}$</p>",
